Mushroom Classification Analysis¶

Introduction¶

In this notebook, we will perform a comprehensive analysis of the mushroom dataset to classify mushrooms as edible or poisonous. The goal is to build a robust machine learning model that can accurately distinguish between these two classes based on various mushroom characteristics.

Dataset Overview¶

  • Number of Instances: 8,124
  • Number of Attributes: 22 (all categorical)
  • Target Variable: class (edible or poisonous)
  • Missing Values: 2,480 missing values in the stalk_root attribute.

Key Steps:¶

  1. Data Preprocessing: Handle missing values, encode categorical features, and split the data.
  2. Model Training: Train multiple classification models and evaluate their performance.
  3. Feature Importance Analysis: Visualize feature importances from trained models.
  4. Feature Selection: Use Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE), Mutual Information, and Chi-Square tests to identify the most important features.
  5. Re-analysis: Drop the odor feature and repeat the analysis to see its impact on model performance.
  6. Conclusion: Summarize findings and identify the minimal feature set for perfect classification.

Let's dive into the analysis!

Data Preprocessing¶

Before we can train our models, we need to preprocess the data. This involves handling missing values, encoding categorical features, and splitting the data into training and testing sets.

Step 1: Load and Clean the Data¶

  • Load the dataset: We'll start by loading the dataset from the CSV file.
  • Handle missing values: The stalk_root column has 2,480 missing values. We'll drop this column to simplify our analysis.
  • Encode categorical features: Since all features are categorical, we'll use one-hot encoding to convert them into numerical format.
  • Split the data: We'll split the data into training (70%) and testing (30%) sets.

Why One-Hot Encoding?¶

Categorical features (e.g., cap_shape, cap_color) cannot be directly used in machine learning models because they are not numerical. One-hot encoding converts these categorical features into binary vectors, where each category is represented as a separate column with a value of 0 or 1. This allows models to process categorical data effectively.

One-Hot Encoding¶

Since all features are categorical, we'll use one-hot encoding to convert them into numerical format. This will allow us to use them in machine learning models.

Since I want to use precision to ensure that mushrooms predicted as edible are indeed edible, I must encode the target such that 'e' (edible) is the positive class (i.e., {'e': 1, 'p': 0}). This is because the default value of pos_label in scikit-learn's precision_score and recall_score is 1, and these metrics are calculated with respect to the positive class.

Why This Matters

Precision measures how many of the predicted positives are actually positive.

If 'e' (edible) is the positive class (1), precision will measure how many mushrooms predicted as edible are indeed edible.

If 'p' (poisonous) is the positive class (1), precision will measure how many mushrooms predicted as poisonous are indeed poisonous.

If you want to change the positive class, you can explicitly set pos_label to the desired value (e.g., pos_label=0 to treat 'e' as positive when encoded as 0).

In [25]:
# Let's transform 'e' (edible) and 'p' (poisonous) into 1 and 0 respectively.
target_encoding = {'e':1, 'p':0}
Y_onehot = Y.map(target_encoding)

Model Training and Evaluation¶

Step 2: Train Multiple Models¶

We will train and evaluate the following models:

  • Naive Bayes: A probabilistic classifier based on Bayes' theorem. It assumes that features are independent of each other, making it fast and simple.
  • Random Forest: An ensemble of decision trees that reduces overfitting by averaging multiple trees. It is robust and handles non-linear relationships well.
  • Decision Tree: A tree-based model that splits the data based on feature values. It is interpretable but prone to overfitting.
  • Logistic Regression: A linear model for binary classification. It models the probability of the target class using a logistic function.
  • SVC (Linear/RBF): Support Vector Machine with different kernels. Linear SVC works well for linearly separable data, while RBF SVC can handle non-linear data.
  • KNN: Classification based on nearest neighbors. It predicts the class of a sample based on the majority class of its k-nearest neighbors.
  • XGBoost: A gradient boosting algorithm that builds trees sequentially, correcting errors from previous trees. It is highly accurate and scalable.

Why Multiple Models?¶

Different models have different strengths and weaknesses. By comparing multiple models, we can identify the best-performing one for this dataset.

Feature Selection Techniques¶

Step 4: Identify Important Features¶

We will use the following techniques to select the most important features:

  • Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE): Recursively removes the least important features and builds the model until the specified number of features is reached.
  • Mutual Information: Measures the dependency between features and the target. Higher mutual information indicates a stronger relationship.
  • Chi-Square Test: Evaluates the relationship between categorical features and the target. It is particularly useful for categorical data.

Why Feature Selection?¶

Feature selection helps us:

  • Reduce overfitting by removing irrelevant features.
  • Improve model performance by focusing on the most important features.
  • Reduce training time and computational cost.

Feature Selection: Dropping Some Features¶

To refine our dataset, we’ll remove certain features that are impractical for real-world use.

  1. Dropping 'odor':

    • Reason 1: To increase the challenge for classifiers, as they currently rely heavily on this feature.
    • Reason 2: To focus exclusively on visual characteristics of the mushrooms, making the model more aligned with practical scenarios where only visual inspection is possible.

  2. Dropping 'population' and 'habitat':

    • Reason: These features are not directly observable when handling a mushroom. Since our goal is to create a model that works with immediate, observable attributes, these features are excluded.

Let's first remove 'odor' only¶

# Set Seaborn style for better aesthetics
sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")

# Loop through each column and plot a horizontal bar chart
for column in aggregated_df.columns:
    # Filter out features with zero importance
    non_zero_features = aggregated_df[column][aggregated_df[column] != 0]
    
    # Check if there are any non-zero features to plot
    if not non_zero_features.empty:
        # Create the plot
        plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
        
        # Use Seaborn's barplot with `hue` and `legend=False`
        sns.barplot(
            x=non_zero_features.sort_values(),
            y=non_zero_features.sort_values().index,
            hue=non_zero_features.sort_values().index,  # Assign y to hue
            palette="coolwarm",
            alpha=0.8,
            legend=False
        )
        
        # Add labels and title
        plt.xlabel('Feature Importance', fontsize=12, labelpad=10)
        plt.ylabel('Feature', fontsize=12, labelpad=10)
        plt.title(f'Feature Importances - {column}', fontsize=14, pad=20, weight='bold')
        
        # Add data labels (importance values) to the bars
        for i, v in enumerate(non_zero_features.sort_values()):
            plt.text(v + 0.01, i, f'{v:.3f}', color='black', va='center', fontsize=10)
        
        # Remove spines (borders) for a cleaner look
        sns.despine(left=True, bottom=True)
        
        # Adjust layout for better spacing
        plt.tight_layout()
        
        # Show the plot
        plt.show()
    else:
        print(f"No non-zero feature importances found for {column}.")

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import make_scorer, precision_score

# Define the model
model = xgb.XGBClassifier(random_state=42, eval_metric='logloss')

# Define the parameter grid to search
param_grid = {
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7],  # Maximum depth of a tree
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.2],  # Step size shrinkage
    'n_estimators': [50, 100, 200],  # Number of boosting rounds
    'subsample': [0.8, 1.0],  # Subsample ratio of the training instances
    'colsample_bytree': [0.8, 1.0],  # Subsample ratio of columns when constructing each tree
    'scale_pos_weight': [1, 12]  # Control the balance of positive and negative weights
}

# Use precision as the scoring metric
scorer = make_scorer(precision_score)

# Perform grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=model,
    param_grid=param_grid,
    scoring=scorer,  # Optimize for precision
    cv=5,  # 5-fold cross-validation
    n_jobs=-1  # Use all available CPU cores
)

# Use precision as the scoring metric
scorer = make_scorer(precision_score)

# Perform grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(model, param_grid, scoring=scorer, cv=5)
grid_search.fit(X_filtered_train, y_filtered_train)

# Get the best model
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
print(f"Best params: {best_params}")
